<HEADLINE>
FT  20 NOV 92 / British Gas hit by competition and prices cap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH GAS showed yesterday how far it is coming under pressure from
increased competition and a cap on domestic gas prices when it reported a
pre-tax loss of Pounds 282m for the third quarter which was higher than many
in the City had expected.
Mr Cedric Brown, British Gas chief executive, said he was disappointed with
the results: 'What they demonstrate is the squeeze we're in is continuing.'
In the same period last year, warmer-than-normal weather had led to a
pre-tax loss of Pounds 318m on an historic cost basis. The effects of colder
weather this year have been more than offset by price controls and rising
competition in the industrial gas market.
The company said that 42 per cent of the firm contract market for gas -
about half of the entire industrial market - is now supplied by rivals.
British Gas has been forced to lower its prices to domestic gas consumers
twice by pressure from the regulator.
In the first nine months of the year, profits slipped to Pounds 633m from
Pounds 989m in the previous year. Analysts have cut forecasts for full-year
earnings to Pounds 850m-Pounds 950m, against Pounds 1.2bn last year.
Mr Brown said he recognised the need to reduce costs, in an attempt to
offset pressure from competition and lower prices, but was unable to make
sweeping cutbacks or initiate any big restructuring before hearing the
results of an inquiry by the Monopolies and Mergers Commission into British
Gas's business.
British Gas took the unprecedented step of submitting itself to an MMC
inquiry in July after it became frustrated with its regulator. The MMC
review has shrouded the company's entire UK business in uncertainty.
The company is looking to its exploration and production business for future
growth, although it has retreated from its goal of achieving 40 per cent of
its profits from this division by the end of the decade. 'We want to achieve
a better balance between the businesses', said Mr Brown, 'and our main drive
is to convert proven reserves into production which will start generating
earnings.'
Nevertheless, the company has cut capital expenditure from Pounds 2.8bn this
year to Pounds 2bn in an effort to control costs. Its shares were little
changed yesterday, edging up from 279p to 279.5p.
