<HEADLINE>
FT  20 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tory Euro-sceptics prepare for new
battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CLASHES between Tory Euro-sceptics and the government will resume in the
next two weeks against the backdrop of a Commons' committee report yesterday
warning of difficulties ahead in ratifying the Maastricht treaty.
MPs will debate developments in the European Community and its financing on
Tuesday. The following week they will start the committee stage of the
Maastricht treaty bill.
About 300 amendments have already been proposed to the Maastricht bill.
Little headway is expected in the two or three days to be set aside before
Christmas.
Mr John Major begins a tour of European capitals on Monday, starting in
Brussels. He hopes to make progress towards agreement at next month's
Edinburgh EC summit on how Danish objections to Maastricht can be overcome
and on defining subsidiarity - making decisions at the lowest possible
level.
Downing Street indicated yesterday that the prime minister may concede a
discussion at Edinburgh on joint action to end recession - possibly
including European Commission proposals based on monetary co-operation and
public works.
Officials said the summit would 'certainly' discuss economic growth. Any
fresh proposals, however, would have to take into account the EC's past
commitment to 'sound public finance' and reduction of government deficits.
Downing Street continues to emphasise the importance of a deal on the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
In its report, the cross-party Commons foreign affairs select committee says
that EC leaders' hope of agreeing at Edinburgh on how subsidiarity can be
applied in principle 'will be difficult to achieve'.
It argues that challenges in the European Court of Justice against community
action under the subsidiarity articles in the Maastricht treaty are unlikely
to succeed and that without a new institutional mechanism for enforcing
subsidiarity, they will not be effective. 'Subsidiarity is best understood
as a political or constitutional convention, rather than a legal mechanism,'
the report says.
The MPs also say it is 'unclear' how the changes to Maastricht needed before
a second Danish referendum can be made legally binding, while upholding the
agreement of other EC countries not to renegotiate the treaty. The MPs say
it is 'not known' how changes for Denmark will affect ratification in the
UK. The British government, in its capacity as president of the European
Community, bore a special responsibility in the failure to find a solution
to the Yugoslav crisis, Dr John Cunningham, the shadow foreign secretary
said yesterday.
Dr Cunningham was particularly critical of the Community's and Britain's
'failure of will' in enforcing sanctions against Serbia and other former
Yugoslav regions.
</TEXT>
