FT  20 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: MPs' pay freeze under attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   A GOVERNMENT proposal to freeze MPs' pay at its present level
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Pounds 30,854 - should be opposed, Ms Harriet Harman, Labour's shadow chief
secretary, told the Commons last night.
She called for the agreement linking rises in MPs' pay to that of
middle-ranking civil servants to continue. Under that agreement, MPs would
receive an increase of 3.9 per cent from January. The allowance MPs receive
for their office costs was increased by more than Pounds 10,000 last July.
Conservative MPs will be subject to a two-line whip on the proposal, due to
be debated on Wednesday, while Labour backbenchers will be allowed a free
vote.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, the deputy leader, said yesterday that the party
leadership's intention was to abstain, but that might be reviewed in the
light of the terms of the government motion.
Ms Harman's move came during the resumed debate on the chancellor's Autumn
Statement in response to Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the
Treasury.
Ms Harman recalled that the link with civil servants' pay was made to stop
the remuneration of MPs being a 'political football'. She challenged Tory
MPs 'baying for a pay freeze' to observe the 1.5 per cent ceiling set by the
government for public-sector workers and to refuse increases in the fees
they received from directorships.
She was joined by other Labour MPs in arguing that the growing number of
redundancies underlined the failure of the Autumn Statement to provide the
stimulus needed for for recovery.
Mr Portillo maintained that the Autumn Statement would create the conditions
for a return of confidence and would remove the barrier to growth.
Mr John Townend, MP for Bridlington and chairman of the Conservative
backbench finance committee, warned that unless there was another 'assault'
on public spending next year, the alternative of an increase in taxation
would have to be faced.
He urged ministers to remember what had happened to departing US President
George Bush after his pledge not to raise taxes, and warned them that the
Conservatives had won the election because voters believed they would not
put up taxes.
Mr Nick Brown, in the final speech from the Labour front bench, emphasised
that the increase in unemployment was the largest single factor affecting
consumer confidence.
An attempt by Labour to condemn the Autumn Statement was defeated by 55
votes (322-267). A second attempt by Labour to attack the government's
policy came to a premature end when the party's whips failed to appoint
tellers for the vote. Miss Betty Boothroyd, the Speaker, ruled that the
division could not take place, which resulted in a motion approving the
Autumn Statement being carried without challenge.
