<HEADLINE>
FT  20 NOV 92 / October lending sharply up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BIG rise in lending by banks and building societies last month encouraged
hopes that the economy may be on the mend.
The increase was partly a rebound from a large repayment of loans in
September, while demand by consumers for bank credit remains weak.
Lending by banks and building societies in sterling increased in October by
a seasonally adjusted Pounds 5.1bn, the biggest monthly figure for nearly
two years, the Bank of England said yesterday.
The rise followed a repayment of loans of Pounds 1.1bn in September. Mr
Simon Briscoe, an economist at brokers Greenwell Montagu, said that the
figures for the two months showed the economy was 'still weak'.
The British Bankers' Association said the nine biggest UK commercial banks
increased lending by a seasonally adjusted Pounds 3.2bn last month, the
biggest rise since February 1990. It followed a repayment of loans to those
banks of Pounds 1.3bn in September.
The rise in bank lending partly reflected large borrowing by manufacturers
to pay corporation tax. Manufacturers increased lending by Pounds 728m, on a
non-seasonally-adjusted basis, the biggest rise since June 1988.
Against that, demand from consumers remains weak. Although lending for house
purchases continued to rise the increase of Pounds 335m lent for mortgages
from the nine banks was the smallest since January.
Excluding mortgages, consumers repaid credit to the nine banks of Pounds
542m, the largest repayment since the BBA started monthly records in 1986.
Other Bank of England figures showed the amount of money in the economy
expanding modestly in October. M0, the narrow measure of the money supply,
mainly comprising notes and coins in circulation, rose a seasonally adjusted
0.6 per cent in October to show a year-on-year rise of 2.4 per cent. In the
year to September, the figure was 2.3 per cent.
M4, a broader measure, which takes in bank and building society deposits as
well as notes and coins, increased by 1.0 per cent in October. The
year-on-year rise was 5.4 per cent, as against 5.1 per cent in the 12 months
to September.
Britain's public-sector borrowing requirement was overfunded by Pounds 9.1bn
in the first six months of the 1992-93 financial year, the Bank of England
reported yesterday.
The overfund reflected drawings on the UK foreign currency reserves to
defend sterling in September; foreign borrowing by the government; and
official sales of government gilt-edged stock.
</TEXT>
