<HEADLINE>
FT  20 NOV 92 / Brazilian President denies dithering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB and JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRAZIL's new President Itamar Franco has defended himself against mounting
criticism he is spending his time on trivia rather than the economic
problems confronting the country.
In his first lengthy press conference since taking office two months ago, Mr
Franco said: 'Society wants the president sometimes to put aside
macrothinking and descend to the microlevel of rents, medicines, schools and
trying to improve everyday life.'
His focus on such issues has led his administration to be labelled 'the
Cheese Muffin Republic', a reference to the muffin staple diet of Brazil's
poor.
The president was to outline his plans for government in his first national
address on Wednesday but cancelled it to visit his sick mother. Later he
made clear some of his views, declaring war on financial speculators who
have been leaving the stockmarket and buying gold and dollars. 'As long as
I'm President there will be this war without mercy.'
Referring to Mr Collor's recent comments that he was dragging Brazil into
the fifth world, Mr Franco said 'the misery we have today puts us far below
the fifth world. Two and a half years of Collor's high interest rates and
violent monetary policy have left us with deep recession and millions of
Brazilians living in absolute poverty.'
For the first time in living memory, a senior public figure has been found
guilty of corruption in Argentina. The Senate yesterday impeached Mr Alberto
Nicosia, a federal judge accused of multi-million-dollar fraud against state
companies, John Barham reports from Buenos Aires. The senators found the
judge guilty of misconduct and failing to carry out the duties of a public
official. They removed him from the bench and banned him from holding public
office.
</TEXT>
