FT  20 NOV 92 / Housing starts in US show decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A RUN OF encouraging US economic news was broken yesterday by reports of an
unexpected decline in housing starts in October and a sharp rise in weekly
claims for unemployment insurance early this month, writes Michael Prowse
from Washington.
The Commerce Department said housing starts fell 1.1 per cent between
September and October to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.23m units.
The decline was broadly based with fewer starts in all regions except the
Midwest. The figures, however, tend to be volatile on a monthly basis.
The number of people making new claims for state unemployment insurance rose
31,000 to 386,000 in the week ending November 7, the largest increase in
three months. The jump came as a surprise after weeks of steady declines.
