<HEADLINE>
FT  20 NOV 92 / World Trade News: US, EC claim 'progress' on oilseeds deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TRADE NEGOTIATORS from the US and European Community ended crucial talks in
Washington last night, with both sides claiming to have made 'very good
progress'.
The discussions were aimed at averting a transatlantic trade war over
European oilseed subsidies and at reviving stalled Uruguay Round talks on
world trade liberalisation.
Officials said that the US-EC talks would continue at a later date, though
it was not disclosed when.
The two sides are negotiating under a deadline, as US punitive sanctions
against some European goods are due to come into force on December 5 in
retaliation for European subsidies to oilseeds farmers.
In a brief but upbeat statement both sides insisted that 'very good
progress' had been made in the talks, which began on Wednesday night.
Mrs Carla Hills, the US Trade Representative, said: 'We are very close
together and we are going to continue to work. We will meet again as soon as
possible. We have to gather some other data.'
Mr Frans Andriessen, the EC external affairs commissioner, said: 'We have
had a good consultation which contributed to finding solutions to points we
still have to settle between us.'
Mr Ray MacSharry, the EC's agriculture commissioner, said: 'We are almost at
an agreement.'
Earlier, after Wednesday night's session, the sides said they had been far
apart on critical issues. Differences included:
A significant gap between proposed US and EC ceilings on oilseeds
production;
Whether or not oilseeds grown for industrial use on set-aside land should be
included in the deal;
EC refusal to accept a formal or binding enforcement mechanism to ensure
corrective action and compensation if EC farmers overshoot output ceilings.
As the two sides resumed talks yesterday, Mrs Hills said she wanted above
all to be able to announce agreement by the time talks ended last night.
Meanwhile, tempers flared elsewhere. Some 300 French farmers burned the US
flag and hurled fireworks over police lines barring them from the US embassy
in Paris.
Twenty police were injured in the clash, intended to put pressure on the EC
'not to allow the US to step on our feet and sacrifice European and French
agriculture'. In Washington, Mr Steve Yoder, American Soyabean Association
president, and a leading lobbyist against the EC oilseeds regime, said he
was 'disgusted' by the French farmers.
France would not be mollified by any US concessions in the non-farm aspects
of the Gatt talks into accepting what it saw as a bad farm trade deal, Mr
Jean-Pierre Soisson, French agriculture minister, said.
Despite the demonstrations in Paris, President Francois Mitterrand is
keeping his counsel on whether to invoke a last-resort veto of an agreement
in Washington.
'This (the Gatt) is one of the hardest dossiers I have had to deal with
since 1951,' he was quoted as telling his cabinet. Mr Mitterrand clearly
fears an EC crisis if he vetoes a Gatt deal, and a domestic crisis if he
does not. Mr Soisson said yesterday an eventual French veto in the EC
Council of Ministers was for the president to decide.
Mr Soisson said that while France wanted progress in the Gatt areas of
services, market access and copyright protection, it would not be bought off
by concessions here. 'The agricultural chapter must be improved, and the
whole book be made readable,' he added. France would not agree to a rushed
Gatt agreement, he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
