<HEADLINE>
FT  20 NOV 92 / Romanian government approved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIRGINIA MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUCHAREST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Romanian parliament yesterday accepted a new cabinet led by Prime
Minister Nicolae Vacaroiu and committed to gentler reforms.
The cabinet is dominated by the Democratic National Salvation Front (DNSF)
which won 28 per cent of the vote in September's elections. It includes
several junior ministers who served in the communist era and favours a
slower reform.
However, the cabinet is weighted towards the party's younger wing and brings
many newcomers to the government. It also includes some reform-minded
independents, such as Mr Misu Negritoiu, who will be deputy prime minister
in charge of economic reforms.
Romanian nationalist parties which captured 12 per cent of the vote did not,
as feared by many, win cabinet posts.
The democratic convention, a coalition of anti-communist parties which came
second in the polls, voted against the government because it said it failed
to present concrete economic policies.
Mr Vacaroiu said he would not present a long-term strategy for four months.
