<HEADLINE>
FT  20 NOV 92 / Brussels warns of growing jobs toll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Henning Christophersen, EC economics commissioner, yesterday backed calls
for a Community-led growth package, warning that unemployment next year was
likely to rise to 11 per cent amid sluggish growth of between 1 per cent and
1.5 per cent.
Mr Christophersen said he hoped the EC summit in Edinburgh next month would
send a strong signal of support for co-ordinated action based on a
multi-billion dollar public works programme and joint efforts with Japan and
the US to put 'more steam' into the world economy. In a speech in Brussels,
Mr Christophersen implied that the package could entail dilution of the
conditions for the EC's planned shift to a common currency, particularly
over budget deficits.
The Danish commissioner said: 'What we are seeing is more a lack of revenue
(rather) than expenditures getting out of control. Under these
circumstances, it would be understandable if some member states do not
compensate fully on the revenue side.'
Any suggestion of backsliding on the 'convergence criteria' set out in the
Maastricht treaty will alarm Germany. The Bonn government and the Bundesbank
agreed to sacrifice the D-Mark for a common European currency only on
condition that member states met strict criteria on inflation and budget
discipline.
This week, Mr Helmut Schlesinger, Bundesbank president, criticised the
convergence criteria as inadequate and warned against 'lazy compromises' in
selecting countries for monetary union. Mr Christophersen's view that budget
deficit criteria may have to be eased in the short-term is shared by Mr
Jacques Delors, European president.
</TEXT>
