<HEADLINE>
FT  20 NOV 92 / International Company News: O&amp;Y agrees collateral deal with
creditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; York, once the world's biggest real estate developer, is likely to
shrink to a modest-sized property manager during the next few months under
an agreement hammered out with its creditors.
In return for an eight-week postponement of votes on a contentious
debt-restructuring plan, the Reichmann family, O&amp;Y's owners, have agreed to
allow creditors to seize collateral after January 15 and not to obstruct
their efforts in the US courts.
Among the assets which are almost certain to be seized are First Canadian
Place, O&amp;Y's 72-storey flagship in the heart of Toronto's financial
district, and Scotia Plaza, a modern 68-storey building nearby.
A spokesman for one group of creditors said yesterday that 'by the middle of
January, we should have our building unless someone wants to buy our debt.'
O&amp;Y has already lost control of Canary Wharf in London's Docklands and some
of its properties in New York, including 55 Water Street, which is the
world's biggest office building.
The Reichmanns' latest humiliation came in the wake of fierce opposition to
a debt-restructuring proposal presented by O&amp;Y last month.
The opposition was led by Canadian banks and bondholders with claims secured
by specific buildings, who were confident they would be better off seizing
their collateral than agreeing to the concessions proposed by O&amp;Y.
Under this week's agreement, expected to be approved by an Ontario court on
Monday, O&amp;Y must file a new restructuring plan for its 34 creditor groups by
December 15, with votes to be held no later than January 15. Under the old
plan, the votes were to be held between November 25 and 30. A lawyer for one
group of creditors said yesterday 'the revised plan will in effect be a
liquidation.'
