<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Public 'believes profits are used to increase dividends'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST PEOPLE think a big British company would be most likely to use a large
profit to increase dividends and managers' bonuses, according to the latest
British Social Attitudes survey.
The survey, conducted by Social and Community Planning Research, found 54
per cent believed this would happen, while only 3 per cent thought it should
be the company's first priority.
A total of 42 per cent favoured investing in machinery, technology, training
and research, but only 28 per cent believed it was what the company would
do.
A more striking variation between beliefs and expectations arose over
sharing profits with employees. Only 8 per cent thought a company would
improve pay and working conditions as its first priority, while 39 per cent
said it should. In the view of 90 per cent of respondents, owners,
shareholders, directors and managers benefit most from the profits of
British companies - although only 21 per cent think this should be so.
Using profits to pay bonuses to top managers - seen by 20 per cent as the
most likely course of action - was, says the report, favoured by virtually
no one. 'This must cast some doubt on any arguments that Britain has become
an opportunity society,' it adds.
British Social Attitudes. Dartmouth Publishing, Gower House, Croft Road,
Aldershot, Hants GU11 3HR. Pounds 19.95.
</TEXT>
