<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Bhutto under house arrest after march
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FARHAN BOKHARI and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISLAMABAD
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE PAKISTAN government yesterday despatched opposition leader Ms Benazir
Bhutto to the southern city of Karachi and placed her under house arrest
after she tried to lead a huge protest march on the capital Islamabad in an
attempt to bring down the government.
In a show of force Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif flooded the capital and
approach roads with troops who fired on protesters and beat them with
sticks. Hundreds were arrested including Ms Bhutto and the main leaders of
her opposition Pakistan People's party.
Ms Bhutto contends that the conservative Islamic government of Mr Sharif is
corrupt, repressive and came to power through rigging elections in 1990. She
led the 18km long march from Rawalpindi to parliament in Islamabad to demand
the government's dismissal and another election.
Although he commands a majority in parliament, Mr Sharif was unnerved by Ms
Bhutto's promise to storm the capital and may have over-reacted.
Police attacked Ms Bhutto and her supporters with batons after they broke
through barbed-wire barricades erected around her house in Islamabad.
Ms Bhutto, who wore a bullet-proof vest, was hit several times.
Later on the way to nearby Rawalpindi to begin the march police fired dozens
of tear-gas shells at her vehicle. He subsequent arrest only helped to fan
the anger of the crowds. In Rawalpindi protestersfought thousands of riot
police
and security forces battled to restore order in Islamabad and elsewhere in
the country.
'My arrest won't make any difference. The struggle will continue,' Ms Bhutto
told the main opposition crowd - estimated in some reports at 30,000 to
40,000 - in a brief address before being driven away.
She was then flown to Karachi where she was placed under house arrest. She
was also banned from the capital, Islamabad, for 30 days.
In Karachi, police said Ms Bhutto and her mother, Nusrat Bhutto, would be
confined to their homes in the city which have been designated as sub-jails
by Sind province's Home Affairs department. Prison regulations will apply to
the house. Government officials said she had been taken into protective
custody and no charges had been brought.
Yesterday's march represented the biggest challenge yet to the government of
Mr Sharif, who was elected after Ms Bhutto was sacked for alleged corruption
by President Ghulam Ishaq Khan in 1990.
</TEXT>
