FT  19 NOV 92 / De Klerk moves to defuse row over army scandal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT FW de Klerk last night moved to repair damage caused by
accusations of an army dirty tricks campaign against the African National
Congress by replacing the command of South African military intelligence.
In a statement after a 10-hour cabinet meeting, Mr De Klerk said that
General Pierre Steyn, the chief of the Defence Force Staff, had been placed
in immediate command of all intelligence organisations of the armed forces.
The president also ordered some military intelligence files to be seized.
Mr De Klerk by said he had ordered Gen Steyn and Police General Alwyn
Conradie to 'secure immediate control over all the documentation of the
Directorate of Covert Collection (of military intelligence).
The measures came in response to a statement by a judicial inquiry on Monday
that said military intelligence had sought to involve the armed wing of the
ANC, led by Mr Nelson Mandela, in common crime.
Mr De Klerk said he was seeking an urgent meeting with the inquiry's leader,
Judge Richard Goldstone, who has been appointed by the government to probe
the causes of the political violence which is racking the country. The two
will discuss the judge's request that he be given more resources to
investigate wrongdoing by all armed groups in the country.
Earlier further pressure on the government came from Mr Harry Schwartz, the
South African ambassador to the US, who said he was 'furious and outraged'
at the Goldstone Commission disclosures.
'It has undermined all our effort here, all the hard work that so many
people have put into changing our situation here. There can be no room for
this sort of thing in South Africa,' said Mr Schwartz.
The revelations have been a considerable embarrassment to the government as
they cast doubt on the veracity of previous pledges to stop covert campaigns
against political opponents. They have also impeded efforts to revive the
constitutional negotiation process, stalled since May.
The ANC has called for an expanded judicial inquiry into the military,
echoing Judge Goldstone's request for wider powers, more resources and
greater co-operation in carrying out his investigations.
Meanwhile, Mr Gene Louw, minister of defence, said he 'seriously disputed'
several of Judge Goldstone's statements about the affair.
</TEXT>
