FT  19 NOV 92 / Labour acts on union votes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Labour party has moved closer to radically reducing union influence in
policy making with plans to give votes at its annual conference to MPs, MEPs
and possibly local councillors.
However the Labour/Trade Union Review Group, which met yesterday, decided
not to end union influence from the selection of local candidates and the
election of the party leader and deputy leader.
Instead of the idea of 'one member, one vote' in such elections, the review
group has backed the creation of a new category of 'registered supporters'
for union members paying a political levy who are not members of the party.
Registered supporters would have to be consulted in elections for the party
leaders and in local selection elections.
The paper presented to yesterday's meeting was not formally approved but is
expected to go virtually unchanged to a meeting of the party's National
Executive early next year. ever'.
The paper recommends cutting the unions' block vote from 70 per cent to 50
per cent and ensuring that votes are cast by actual delegates rather than
through card votes wielded by union leaders.
On the role of MPs and MEPs the paper says: 'In virtually all sister
socialist parites elected representatives have a direct, individual, vote at
conference'. MPs have no vote at the Labour conference and many say they
would prefer not to have one so as to avoid potential conflict with their
constituency parties.
</TEXT>
