<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Exams league table fiercely attacked: A north-south divide
appears in rankings which have been published for the first time
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PUBLICATION by the gov-ernment of this year's GCSE and A-level examination
results for schools in England caused fierce controversy yesterday.
Mr John Patten, education secretary, hailed the exercise - involving the
issue of 3m booklets - as central to the Citizen's Charter, enabling parents
to make informed choices about schools for their children.
Opposition parties, teachers' unions and an array of educationalists
denounced the results tables as seriously misleading because they presented
'raw' results, making no allowance for socio-economic factors.
The booklets detailing results achieved by all state schools and about a
quarter of private schools will be distributed under the Parent's Charter,
at a cost of Pounds 1.4m. Separate booklets for each of England's 108 local
authority areas will be available through schools, libraries and from
telephone request lines.
Ranked by GCSE performance, London boroughs come top and bottom. After the
Scilly Isles, with its one secondary school, are the London boroughs of
Harrow and Kingston. Tower Hamlets, Barking and Southwark, all of which have
large areas of deprivation, come bottom.
Mr Philip Hygate, chief executive of Isles of Scilly council, said the isles
position at the top of the table was not an aberration. 'It demonstrates the
importance that education has on the Isles of Scilly. It is a historical and
cultural issue.' The Isles of Scilly had compulsory education 30 years
before the rest of the country. 'Almost 100 per cent of our pupils go on to
A-levels or further education,' said Mr Hygate.
Mr Patten said the tables 'mark the start of an information revolution,
bringing an end to a system which has too often denied parents the right to
know how schools are performing'.
The National Confederation of Parent Teacher Associations condemned the
tables as 'lies, damned lies and school exam statistics'.
Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary, said: 'No parents should set too
much store by raw results which cannot reflect the real achievements of
schools - unless viewed with caution tables could unfairly damage the
reputation of a school.'
Mr Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the 179,000-strong National
Association of Schoolmasters and Union of Women Teachers, said the tables
'do nothing more than confirm the obvious'. He said: 'Children in the
gin-and-tonic belt of the south-east do better than those from the poorer
areas of the country.'
The tables are only the first instalment. Next year all primary schools and
their results in the national tests for seven-year-olds will be included.
Results from all independent schools will also be included, as will
information on national curriculum test results for 14-year-olds, truancy
rates and school-leaver destinations.
LEAs and the independent sector complained yesterday at the way the tables
were compiled.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-6739</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKSC7AGDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921119
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / GEC unions win enhanced pay-offs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNION negotiators yesterday claimed victory when GEC Avery, the
Birmingham-based weighing equipment subsidiary of the UK electronics and
electrical engineering group, agreed to restore an enhanced redundancy pay
agreement for more than 2,000 workers.
The agreement, due to be signed today, wins back the right to redundancy pay
for workers employed before April 6. It had been cut about two years ago as
part of an economy drive. The move follows a damages award by the High Court
to a former employee made redundant on inferior terms.
The company has agreed to pay unions' court costs of Pounds 130,000.
</TEXT>
