<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / International Company News: TWA wrangle takes fresh twist
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE long-running wrangle between interested parties at Trans World Airlines,
the bankrupt US carrier owned by Mr Carl Icahn, took a new twist yesterday,
as the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation, the federal agency which
underpins pension benefits in the US, rejected a proposal from the airline's
creditors.
Part of the proposal would have involved Mr Icahn providing a Dollars 200m
short-term loan to TWA. This would have helped tide the carrier through the
difficult winter period, until it emerged from bankruptcy. But the PBGC said
the proposal would not have given adequate protection to pension plans at
the airline, which it claims are underfunded by Dollars 1.2bn, and would
have allowed Mr Icahn to escape the complex pension situation 'at a small
fraction of his obligations'.
The PBGC struck a deal with the airline, its unsecured creditors and unions
last month. Under this deal, TWA would issue 15-year notes, totalling
Dollars 300m, to cover a portion of the underfunding. The two pension plans
would be closed off shortly before the airline emerged from Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection, so that the agency could then pursue its claims
against Mr Icahn and his other business interests.
The PBGC said yesterday that it was prepared to accept amendments to that
agreement, but that the latest creditors' proposal failed 'to meet the
test', when it came to protection of pension interests.
Sir Colin Marshall, British Airways' chief executive, yesterday reiterated
his unwillingness to go ahead with a Dollars 750m investment in USAir, the
US carrier, if the US aviation authorities insist that the opening-up of
Heathrow Airport is a condition for approving the deal. However, he
suggested there could be 'in-between positions, and certainly there is no
reason why our respective governments cannot agree on the achievement of
those objectives'.
This brought a retort from United Airlines, one of the big three US carriers
opposing the BA/USAir deal in the absence of a aviation pact between the UK
and the US. Mr Stephen Wolf, United's chairman, described BA's
'protectionist posture' as 'not in the interests of consumer, US flag
carrier, their employees and the communities they serve'.
</TEXT>
