FT  19 NOV 92 / UK Company News: Brokers gloom on GMTV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOOD MORNING Television, the new commercial breakfast station, will not
break even at the pre-tax level until 1996 according to James Capel, the
stockbroker.
In a generally gloomy assessment of ITV's financial prospects, the report
says the deteriorating television advertising environment will be offset by
GMTV, which succeeds TV-am, cutting its cost base.
Mr Neil Blackley, media analyst at Capel, has however increased his forecast
loss for GMTV in its first year from Pounds 2.2m to Pounds 3.5m and suggests
that operating break-even will not come until 1995, and the first pre-tax
profit of Pounds 1.5m not until 1997.
GMTV is owned by Carlton Communications, LWT (Holdings), Scottish TV, Walt
Disney and the Guardian and Manchester Evening News.
Capel believes the outlook for UK television advertising has worsened since
September.
