<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Government Bonds: Dutch, Belgian rate cuts dominate trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SMALL interest rate cuts in the Netherlands and Belgium dominated trading in
European government bonds yesterday, leading to a late rally in most
European markets yesterday.
ALTHOUGH Germany was closed for a holiday, the impact fed through into the
German bond market, as speculation mounted that a German interest rate cut
may follow shortly. The German bund future on the London International
Financial Futures &amp; Options Exchange rose  1/4 point to close at 91.26.
Dealers said the reaction was exaggerated because of thin volume due to the
holiday.
THE 10 basis-point cut in the Dutch special advances rate to 8.70 per cent
yesterday pushed Dutch rates below German rates once again. The special
advances rate is comparable to the German repo rate, currently 8.75 per
cent, which added to expectations that the repo rate is set to fall.
The Belgian central bank again moved in tandem with the Dutch, cutting its
overnight rate by five basis points.
'Although German interest rates are on the way down, (yesterday's rate cuts
are) a flimsy reason to conclude that there will be a imminent German rate
cut,' said Mr Klaus Baader, an economist at UBS Phillips and Drew. 'The two
currencies (guilder and Belgian franc) move in tandem, and (the central
banks) have clearly reacted to the strength of the currencies.'
NEWS of the Dutch and Belgian rate cuts prompted renewed buying interest in
the gilts market, even from some foreign accounts which had disappeared
following sterling's exit from the European exchange rate mechanism in
September. A 0.1 per cent increase in retail sales for October helped
improve the tone in the gilts market.
After a quiet day's trading, the market suddenly put on a spurt at the end
of the day, bouncing a full point.
US Treasury prices firmed across the maturity range yesterday after the
Federal Reserve chose to add permanently to reserves.
In late trading the benchmark 30-year government bond was up  13/32 at 101
13/32 , yielding 7.501 per cent. At the short end of the market, the
two-year note was up  5/32 , at 99 15/32 , for a yield of 4.520 per cent.
Trading was subdued throughout the morning. News that the US trade gap
narrowed in September, from Dollars 9bn in the previous month to Dollars
8.3bn was in line with market expectations.
Prices gained ground in the afternoon after the Fed bought coupons outright,
pushing prices higher as dealers covered short positions and retail
investors upped their demand. The market was also helped by the announcement
that the Treasury would sell Dollars 15bn in two-year notes and Dollars
10.75bn in five-year notes next week, in line with market expectations.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 33
</PAGE>
