<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / UK Company News: Willis Corroon tumbles to Pounds 61m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECESSION IN the UK and the continuing weakness of the US insurance market
again depressed profit growth at Willis Corroon.
The UK's largest insurance broker yesterday reported a sharp fall in pre-tax
profits from Pounds 89m to Pounds 60.9m for the nine months to September 30
1992.
Turnover from broking activities rose marginally to Pounds 460.3m (Pounds
457.9m), with growth in new business offset by a decline in premium rates in
the US and the UK downturn.
Income from the underwriting subsidiaries fell to Pounds 36m (Pounds 46.9m),
while interest and investment income fell to Pounds 39.8m (Pounds 52m).
Losses from Hurricane Andrew, which caused widespread damage in parts of
Florida and Louisiana in August, could lead to increases in US premium
rates.
Mr Roger Elliott, executive chairman, was cautious about prospects. He said
that 'for the moment rates remain depressed and, coupled with the normal
seasonal pattern of our business, mean that in the last quarter of this year
we are likely at best to break even.'
Expenses rose to Pounds 419.1m (Pounds 388.5m), but only by 3 per cent on an
underlying basis, largely reflecting the cost of new start-up operations in
Europe and North America. Mr Elliott said the figures for brokerage left out
earnings from many of these new acquisitions in the last 18 months.
'These are generating business for the group, revenues from which will
appear increasingly in our results from 1992 and beyond,' he added.
Claims from underwriting activities fell to Pounds 16.8m (Pounds 28.4m).
Associated undertakings produced profits of Pounds 4.5m (Pounds 4.2m), while
interest payable rose to Pounds 4m (Pounds 3.1m).
</TEXT>
