<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Union Discount talks to bidder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNION Discount, the troubled discount house group, is in talks with a
potential bidder that could lead to the takeover of what is one of the
City's oldest independent financial institutions, it was announced
yesterday.
Cater Allen, London's second biggest discount house behind Gerrard &amp;
National, was strongly tipped yesterday as the potential bidder. The
company, which already owns nearly 3 per cent of Union's shares, refused
comment.
The terse announcement from Union that it was in the 'very preliminary
stages of discussions which may or may not lead to an offer being made' was
prompted by a leap in the group's shares. They ended at 71p, up 10p on the
day, compared with a peak two years ago of 500p.
Union, one of a shrinking band of discount houses, which play a pivotal role
in the Bank of England's dealings with the money markets, has been brought
low in recent years by a disastrous move into leasing and property lending.
Its ill-fated diversification stemmed from the mid-1980s when, along with
other City specialists, it tried to move into a wider range of activities to
reduce its reliance on its core business.
Leasing was responsible for losses of Pounds 5.7m in the first half of the
year, out of a total of Pounds 14.8m, with the core discount house business
returning a loss of Pounds 4m.
The group was forced to take on substantial property interests after a loan
to a property company went bad. It finally sold an Edinburgh property, known
as Apex 123, for Pounds 15.5m two weeks ago at a loss of nearly Pounds 1m.
Discount house shares jumped a week ago as the market digested the impact of
September's upheaval in financial markets on the results of King &amp; Shaxson,
another specialist money market dealer.
However, the reorganisation at Union, under way since Mr George Blunden took
over as chief executive earlier this year, is believed to have led it to
take a cautious approach to the markets. As a result, it is thought to have
benefited far less from the market upheaval than its rivals.
Mr David White, deputy chairman of Cater Allen, which announces results
today, said yesterday: 'We're not making any statement. It's been suggested
on one or two occasions in the past, and we didn't make any statement then
either.'
</TEXT>
