<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Cabinet finalises summit agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR began finalising details of the agenda for next month's
European Community summit in Edinburgh with cabinet colleagues yesterday
before touring EC countries to win allies next week.
The prime minister, who chaired a meeting of virtually the entire cabinet,
is expected to begin consulting with other European leaders on Monday over
an ambitious agenda that Downing Street said would be dominated by the UK's
priorities for the EC. But it is likely to provoke fresh rows among the
community's members.
Dispute is expected over the future financing of the EC. Mr Major believes
he can win backing from Germany and France for his opposition to proposals
for increases put forward by Mr Jacques Delors, European Commission
president.
The task of finding a package of changes to the Maastricht treaty to satisfy
Danes will also dominate the Edinburgh summit.
Britain, meanwhile, wants a clearer definition of subsidiarity - the
principle of decisions being taken at the lowest appropriate level.
Downing Street expressed confidence that headway would be made at Edinburgh
but appeared keen not to raise expectations.
Officials indicated that Britain does not want discussion at Edinburgh of
how economic policies could be co-ordinated to boost growth. They said that
the best way to help job creation would be a deal on in negotiations on the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
Others items on the agenda will include the enlargement of the EC and the
completion of the European single market.
The Netherlands has been pencilled in as Mr Major's first destination. He is
expected to visit all other EC countries over the next few weeks.
Although Mr Major realises he faces an uphill task in reaching deals at
Edinburgh, officials at Downing Street stressed that such a tour was usually
organised by the country holding the EC presidency.
