<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont leads Tories' retreat from
pay policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday appeared to draw further back from the idea of a
national pay policy as Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, insisted that the
1.5 per cent pay limit in the public sector was necessary, but failed to
repeat ministerial encouragement to the private sector to follow suit.
Opening the two-day Commons debate on last week's Autumn Statement, Mr
Lamont emphasised the critical role of a tight control on public spending in
restoring economic confidence and hastening recovery.
The need to protect capital programmes and invest in education and health
had made it essential to adopt 'a firm stance' on public-sector pay in order
to control public spending without restraining the growth of services.
Instead of echoing Mr John Major's urging of similar pay restraint in
industry and business on Monday, however, Mr Lamont contrasted the public
and private sectors, pointing out that many private-sector employees had had
pay cuts and that settlements were at a 25-year low.
The earlier invitation to pay restraint in the private sector drew a sharp
attack from a former Tory cabinet minister. Mr John Biffen criticised the
government for 'wheeling out the wayside pulpit', and said that if wealth
creation meant anything, it meant 'rewards for success'.
While Mr Lamont repeated the exhortation to business to take advantage of
the Autumn Statement measures for sectors such as the housing and motor
industries, Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, warned that such moves
were costly and would not yield the expected benefits. They did not measure
up to the scale of the task.
He pointed out that the proposals made by the chancellor were of a scale the
Tories had derided when Labour had made similar suggestions before the
election as part of a national recovery programme.
Under pressure from Tory backbenchers and from Mr Lamont to explain how he
would finance the extra measures he thought necessary, Mr Brown said that
one possibility was a tax on the utilities.
But his central argument was that people would not have the confidence to
begin spending and investing until the fear of unemployment had receded, and
so an employment policy was a vital element in government efforts to assist
recovery, which even Tories now seemed to accept was necessary.
The government itself was now 'an obstacle to recovery', he added, because
people had no knowledge from week to week of its policy, and no faith that
it would keep to it.
Running through the economic 'experimentation' of the 1980s, Mr Brown mocked
the government's economic policy now as simply being based on Mr Lamont's
judgment. 'Every day is judgment day - Norman's wisdom,' he said.
Like Mr Brown, Mr Alan Beith, for the Liberal Democrats, complained that the
chancellor, having accepted the case for fiscal stimulus, had not done the
job properly.
</TEXT>
