<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / NHS pension scheme to be a Next Steps agency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Health Service pension scheme is to become an agency under the
government's Next Steps initiative in which Civil Service functions are
hived off into arm's-length executive bodies.
An announcement launching the NHS Pensions Agency will be made tomorrow. The
new agency will take over responsibility for handling a pension scheme with
nearly 1.3m members. More than Pounds 3bn passes through the scheme each
year in benefit payments and contributions, and its liabilities are around
Pounds 20bn. Mr Alec Cowan, formerly an official at the Department of
Education, will be chief executive.
As well as being Europe's largest occupational pension scheme, the NHS plan
is also regarded in the pensions industry as particularly complex. It covers
all grades of staff in the service, in which it is not unusual for personnel
to move in and out of NHS employment several times during their working
lives.
The scheme is also unusual in providing pensions for many self-employed
contractors such as general practitioners and dentists.
Agency status will not change the scheme's benefits or funding, and pensions
policy issues will remain with the NHS management executive at the
Department of Health.
'But a range of benefits should flow from agency status,' said Mr Cowan. 'My
priorities will include making better use of computer systems and improving
links with NHS employers to ensure that the pension scheme has the best
possible information flow.
'This is a classic area for a Next Steps agency. The business is well
defined and we know our customers. It is clear, without criticising anybody,
that improvements in administration can be made, and agency status will help
give the pension scheme a stronger and more visible focus.'
</TEXT>
