<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Leading council praises parents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR BILL DICKINSON, director of education for Kingston upon Thames, one of
the top boroughs, believed its excellent results were based on the full
range of good local schools, and not just those that selected their pupils.
'Our schools, as well as being ably led by their head teachers and
management, are also strongly supported by parents and governors,' he said.
'This leads to generally well-motivated pupils.' According to the results,
46.3 per cent of Kingston pupils achieved A-C grades in five or more GCSE
levels compared with a national average of 38.1 per cent. Two schools,
Tiffin Girls' and the Tiffin School (for boys), achieved pass rates of 96
per cent and 92 per cent respectively for these top grades.
Mr Dickinson also thought strong primary schools and the relatively small
size of the borough, which allowed closer contact with schools, were factors
that led to good results.
Ms Sandra Buchanan, headmistress of Tiffin Girls', said it was not
surprising that selective schools such as hers were at the top of the table.
'Kingston is a fairly prosperous borough so it should have good results.'
Southwark, the inner London borough at the bottom of the league table, was
clearly taken aback by its position. It is introducing an action plan to
improve future GCSE results. The borough, which includes former dockland
areas, had an average of 15.1 per cent of pupils achieving top GCSE A-C
grades.
Mr John McTernan, chairman of the education committee, said local results
were better than last year, but 'unacceptable differences in attainment'
remained. He added: 'A lot of difficulties, particularly around teacher
staffing, have been resolved.'
</TEXT>
