<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / How the education authorities compare
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Until today, comparative results have been the private preserve of local
authorities, which, with certain notable and praiseworthy exceptions, seemed
to believe that parents cannot be trusted to understand or use the figures
wisely.  This attitude is now permanently consigned to the dustbin of
educational history.
John Patten, education secretary
This measure is yet another of Mr Patten's diversionary tactics - pretending
he is doing something while, in reality, failing to address the key issue in
schools today - underfunding.  And when it comes to the future of British
education, John Patten comes bottom of my league every time.
Don Foster, Liberal Democrat education spokesman
The arrangements were devised to fit the requirements of computers and are
not a sophisticated analysis to reflect the achievements of pupils or
schools.
Vivian Anthony, secretary of the Headmasters' Conference, representing
leading public schools
There is nothing misleading about it, it is putting information which
parents have a right to know into the public domain.
Baroness Blatch education minister
Just as there is more to life than exam results, so there is more to schools
than raw exam grades.  What about music, art, sport and giving children a
broad-based education for life?
Gillian Wood, assistant general secretary of the Assistant Masters and
Mistresses Association
The government might well reflect upon the fortunes of football where the
league table mentality reigns supreme.  The few clubs at the top attract all
the best players and the money, but what has happened to overall standards
and skills, not to mention behaviour?
Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the 179,000-strong National
Association of Schoolmasters and Union of Woman Teachers
