<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Mines could cut coal prices, MPs told
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT LEAST half the UK pits earmarked for possible closure are capable of
producing coal at cheaper prices than those tentatively agreed between
British Coal and electricity generators, a consultancy advising the
government told MPs yesterday.
Mr Ronald Lewis, of the John T Boyd consultancy, told MPs an investigation
of 28 pits earlier this year demonstrated that within three or four years
they could produce coal at an average of Pounds 1.33p a gigajoule and that
this could fall to Pounds 1.15.
Mr Lewis also backed changes to an 84-year-old law that restricts miners'
underground shifts to 7 1/2 hours.
He said this was necessary partly because of the time miners often needed to
travel long distances to coalfaces, especially in the north-east of England.
Any move to change the law would be strongly opposed by the unions. Mr Peter
McNestry, general secretary of the Nacods pit deputies union, said yesterday
that longer hours would significantly increase the dangers of working in
mines.
British Coal has tentatively agreed contracts with the two main generators
in England and Wales by which it would sell coal at Pounds 1.50. Mr Lewis
said 15 or 16 of 31 pits earmarked for closure would be be able to reach the
Pounds 1.33.
Yesterday's revelations will increase concern that the pit closure programme
is being implemented too hastily. Nonetheless the question of finding a
market for the coal will have to be addressed.
Mr Lewis said: 'When you look at the future of British collieries it is not
a question of whether there will be 50 or 40. It is a case of 40 or less.'
Mr Lewis also disclosed to the Trade and Industry Committee inquiry into
energy policy that Boyd has been asked by the government to rank 21 pits
whose future is under review in order of viability.
The consultancy has not been asked by the government to consider 10 other
pits which British Coal has said will close but which are subject to 90-day
consultation procedures, an omission that surprised some MPs.
Boyd has asked for and been given government approval to look at the 19
remaining British Coal pits always scheduled to remain open, because it
wanted to see 'if they represented the best', Mr Lewis said.
In other evidence the Coalfield Communities Campaign said the market for
coal in the electricity sector could be sustained at 70m tonnes a year or
more throughout the 1990s.
Within the framework they suggested, no electricity supply option, including
nuclear, would be closed off. Power station coal imports could continue
though at a lesser level than present.
CCC's 'modest changes' would enable all pits to stay open and would reduce
the costs of electricity to consumers by Pounds 400m a year.
</TEXT>
