<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Motorists face urban road pricing, warns MacGregor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent and BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John MacGregor, transport secretary, yesterday signalled that motorists
would have to start paying for the use of the roads in London and other
cities in the next few years.
Tolls would be collected electronically, with meters in cars activated by
roadside transmitters clocking up charges according to distance travelled,
vehicle type and time of day.
Mr MacGregor appears to have accepted that charging people on a
pay-as-you-go basis is likely to provide the only feasible long-term
solution to worsening urban traffic congestion. He also has the support of
environment ministers who favour such charges as a means of curbing the rise
in carbon dioxide emissions accompanying rapid traffic growth.
Speaking at a London traffic conference yesterday, Mr MacGregor in effect
launched a campaign to soften up public opinion in readiness for the likely
introduction of road pricing in the late 1990s.
He said no firm decisions would be taken before the completion of a
three-year feasibility study at the end of 1994, but his intention was to
get a debate going.
Mr MacGregor acknowledged that road pricing was likely to prove unpopular,
but said the alternative could be even worse. 'Is increasing congestion, and
ultimately gridlock, a more attractive option?' he asked.
Road pricing would speed up journey times, improve bus services and cut
transport costs, he said. It would also boost trade and commerce by making
cities more attractive places in which to live, shop and work.
Yesterday's initiative marks an about-turn from the policies of Mrs
Thatcher's government, which ruled out road pricing as an infringement of
the motorist's right to drive.
It may yet face opposition from Mr MacGregor's cabinet colleagues, some of
whom will argue that road pricing could turn into a transport version of the
poll tax. Motorists already face the possibility of tolls on trunk roads and
motorways following the chancellor's announcement last week that this would
make it easier for privately-funded toll roads to compete.
The Automobile Association attacked the urban road pricing plan, saying it
would hit the least well-off. It said precedence should be given to better
enforcement of parking controls and improvements in public transport.
Car drivers are cutting back on maintenance because of the recession, the
RAC said yesterday, Bronwen Maddox writes.
In a survey conducted this month in London and Leicester, the motoring
organisation found that 12 per cent of motorists had cut back on servicing.
The survey found that more than half of CO (carbon monoxide) emissions come
from only 13 per cent of vehicles, and one of those emits as much as 40 of
the cleanest.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
