FT  19 NOV 92 / Japan's leaders warned on budget delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO of Japan's most powerful economic policymakers yesterday warned
political leaders that they risked seriously damaging already fragile
business confidence by the prolonged delay in enacting a special budget to
boost the economy.
Mr Yasushi Mieno, the governor of the Bank of Japan, and Mr Takeshi Noda,
the head of the Economic Planning Agency, both warned that the delay to the
Japanese parliament's debate on the budget risked deepening the economic
downturn.
The budget, which is needed to enact the Y10,700bn (Pounds 56.8bn) emergency
spending package announced in August, is being held up by a dispute between
the ruling Liberal Democratic party and the opposition over which LDP
leaders will testify over their involvement in the Tokyo Sagawa Kyubin
scandal.
Further talks yesterday between the LDP and the opposition failed to break
the deadlock. Opposition parties insist they will not convene the
parliamentary budget committee until the LDP agrees to at least five leaders
giving sworn testimony to the legislature.
Mr Noda, presenting a gloomy agency report on the economic outlook, said:
'Public distrust in politics is a big factor in undermining business
sentiment. From the people's point of view the government and the ruling
party - not just the opposition - are responsible for the impasse.'
Mr Mieno warned that a delay would greatly affect business and stock market
sentiment. In a rare comment upon the politics of economic policy, he
remarked: 'We really hope the Diet discussion on the budget will start as
soon as possible.' He said many hard-pressed companies were anxiously
waiting for benefits of the emergency package to flow through.
However, he said he was not considering a cut in the official discount rate,
although he acknowledged the economy was still in the midst of a painful
adjustment. He also said the Bank of Japan had no plans to offer financial
support to a banking industry body set up recently designed to reduce the
banks' bad loans.
A senior Economic Planning Agency official warned that the economy was so
fragile it was only being supported by public works spending and housing
investment.
Meanwhile, even though the special supplementary budget has not been passed
through parliament, pressure is mounting on the Ministry of Finance to
deliver a further fiscal stimulus through the 1993 budget. Concern that
small companies may face a credit crunch from banks' increasingly cautious
approach to lending is an important factor behind the ministry of finance's
decision to sanction a 10 per cent rise next year in the fiscal investment
and loan programme, the so-called second budget.
The ministry has agreed appropriations from the budget should rise to
Y45,000bn next year.
