<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / PM and Patten hold talks
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR, the prime minister, (right) and Mr Chris Patten, Hong Kong's
governor, yesterday discussed strategy in the face of fierce opposition from
China to Mr Patten's proposals for broader democracy in the territory. The
two friends had talks and a private lunch. Mr Patten called for 'calm and
constructive and rational discussions'.
The vehemence of Beijing's objections upset Hong Kong's stock market, which
has fallen 7 per cent in the past two days. Mr Patten said: 'We are very
happy to have discussions about positive proposals for the way forward with
anyone, at any time, anywhere.'
HK airport funding, Page 6
</TEXT>
