<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Philippines may set up new bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MANILA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The World Bank has asked the Philippines to look at the feasibility of
setting up a new bank that would cater to the needs of local exporters
suffering the effects of a strong peso, Reuter reports from Manila.
'I think they are biased towards a separate institution like a Philippine
Eximbank (export-import bank),' trade and industry secretary Rizalino
Navarro said.
He said the proposed bank could tap a Dollars 150m export development fund
from the World Bank.
Mr Navarro said one alternative open to the government was to convert an
existing export-oriented institution.
An Eximbank is seen as an ideal solution to local exporters' financial woes
since it could provide long-term concessional loans and be used as a conduit
for development funds, officials said.
The government could convert the Philippine Export and Guarantee Loan Corp
(Philguarantee) into an eximbank, Mr Navarro said. But the cash-strapped
company would have to be nursed back to health, he said.
</TEXT>
