<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / International Company News: O&amp;Y asks to postpone meetings
over debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; York has asked to postpone a series of meetings scheduled to begin
next week at which the ailing property developer's creditors were due to
vote on its debt-restructuring proposals.
Representatives of two of the 34 creditor groups, who asked not to be
identified, said the company made the request after running into stiff
opposition to the 250-page plan it distributed last month.
O&amp;Y is now expected to propose to its most secured creditors that they can
seize the properties against which their debt is secured. It is also
expected to propose giving unsecured creditors an immediate 90% equity stake
in O&amp;Y.
Opposition to last month's plan has come mainly from Canadian banks and from
bondholders whose claims are secured by specific buildings, including First
Canadian Place, O&amp;Y's 72-storey flagship in Toronto.
Some of these groups are confident that they would be better off seizing
their collateral than agreeing to the concessions proposed by O&amp;Y.
The creditors have demanded a number of concessions in return for agreeing
to delay the votes. The two sides were meeting yesterday afternoon to hammer
out details.
Mr Gerald Greenwald, O&amp;Y president, indicated earlier that the plan might be
modified prior to the votes. An O&amp;Y spokesman said yesterday that
discussions with the creditors were continuing but that 'there has been no
resolution on any amendments to the plan'.
The Ontario court, under whose protection O&amp;Y has been operating since last
May, ordered the meetings to take place between November 25 and 30 in
response to unease among creditors over the mounting costs of the
restructuring effort.
O&amp;Y and the creditors are expected to ask the court within the next few days
to postpone the meetings by about a month.
The restructuring plan covers CDollars 8.6bn (USDollars 6.7bn) of O&amp;Y's
CDollars 13.5bn debt. It excludes Canary Wharf, the London project which is
now under the control of administrators, and negotiations with lenders to
specific O&amp;Y buildings in the US.
The plan proposed the creation of a number of new companies in which
unsecured and under-secured creditors would ultimately be substantial
shareholders.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
