<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / UK pulls out of fast reactor research
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN will announce today its withdrawal from the European Fast Reactor
nuclear research programme, with the loss of up to 400 skilled jobs.
The staff cuts will mainly be at Atomic Energy Authority plants at Risley,
Cheshire, and Dounreay, Caithness.
Withdrawal from the co-operative project with France and Germany spells the
end of UK development of fast reactors - also known as fast breeders.
Unlike conventional nuclear reactors, fast reactors 'breed' their own
plutonium fuel. Since the mid 1950s, the UK government has spent almost
Pounds 2bn on fast reactor research and development.
Mr Brian Eyre, chief executive of AEA Technology, told unions yesterday that
the government would stop paying Pounds 13m a year to fund the UK share of
the research after the project's first design phase ends in March.
The nuclear industry is not prepared to commit its own funds to continue the
programme, which is intended to design a demonstration fast reactor to be
built in the late 1990s, probably in France. The government decided last
summer to close Britain's prototype fast reactor at Dounreay in 1994.
Mr Eyre said he was 'bitterly disappointed' about the government decision
because he believes fast reactors will be essential to achieve the full
potential of nuclear power in the 21st century.
The unions reacted angrily. Mr John Billard, national officer of the
Institution of Professionals, Managers and Specialists, said: 'As we are
pleading with Germany to stay with the European Fighter Aircraft, here we go
pulling out of the EFR. Once again the government is causing huge damage to
Britain's technological capability and international standing by reneging on
its commitments.'
The IPMS said Britain's withdrawal from fast reactor research would leave
the field open not only to France and Germany but also to Russia and Japan,
which were investing heavily in the technology.
But some experts believe that, with uranium and plutonium supplies likely to
remain plentiful for the foreseeable future, fast reactors are an
unnecessary and unwelcome step in the development of nuclear power.
They maintain that it would be better to concentrate on research into fusion
reactors, which are not expected to become available commercially for
another 40 years.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
