<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Companies challenge allegations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Industrial Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE reaction of British companies named in Labour's list as alleged to have
traded in arms and related equipment with Iraq was mostly low-key. It was
claimed that the information was either not new or did not relate to
defence.
British Aerospace reacted dismissively to its inclusion in the list, along
with the Royal Ordnance arms manufacturer which it took over in 1987. The
company said it always scrupulously adheres to government approvals in all
its activities. 'This is a party political activity and we have no comment
on it.'
ICL, the UK-based computing services company now controlled by Fujitsu of
Japan, agreed it had supplied computer peripherals to Iraq during the period
in question but categorically denied that any trade regulations had been
breached.
The company said: 'ICL traded in Iraq until August 1990 and the Iraqi
Ministry of Defence was one of our customers. We provided mainframe computer
equipment to the Iraqi Ministry of Defence between 1988 and 1990.'
Racal is identified as having supplied battlefield radios. The electronics
company said: 'This all came up last year. Racal has historically supplied
tactical radios to Iraq, with the full knowledge of the government and the
relevant export licences. The last orders were taken in the mid-1980s and
the last deliveries were in 1989.'
Thorn EMI said it exported a 'small quantity' of Cymbeline battlefield
radars to Iraq in 1974. Over the following years the electronics group
'received a number of logistics orders' from Iraq. These were for spares,
maintenance and training required for Cymbeline, but it had supplied no new
radars after 1974.
Bimec Industries is also named on the list as having supplied a metal
treatment plant, but yesterday the company said it was no secret that it had
supplied a plant for phosphating and zinc-plating small metallic objects,
along with another plant for spray-painting office furniture, in 1988 and
1989 respectively.
Gatewood Engineering and the former Blackwood Hodge, owned since November
1990 by the BM Group, are named for supplying earth-moving equipment.
Although the financial relationship between the two companies is not clear,
it is understood that Gatewood supplied equipment in Middle East markets
where Blackwood Hodge could not do business because of its trading links
with Israel.
Mr Dick Cameron, a former joint managing director of Blackwood Hodge, said:
'Someone has dreamed up the idea that these 40-tonne off-highway dumptrucks
could be used for carrying bombs.'
Marconi, GEC's defence subsidiary, said it had sold the A-METS artillery
meteorological system to Iraq in 1970 and have since supplied spares, all
under Department of Trade and Industry export licences.
Rolls-Royce said it had supplied refurbished engines for Jet Provost
training aircraft under DTI licence.
The list includes three companies - Astra Holdings, Walter Somers and
Sheffield Forgemasters - involved directly or indirectly in supplying
components for the Iraqi supergun project.
A legal case in connection with the supergun affair against Walter Somers
was dropped on the grounds of insufficient evidence in November 1990. The
company was not available for comment last night, but in evidence submitted
to the Commons trade and industry committee Walter Somers said that it had
been told by the DTI an export licence for steel - supposedly for a
petrochemical project - was not required.
Scott Wilson Kirkpatrick and Partners, a Glasgow-based consultancy, was one
of 36 British companies named earlier this year in a US Senate report, which
suggested it had been involved in the design of air bases and bunkers with
hardened shelters for aircraft in about 1985 or 1986. The company could not
be contacted yesterday. However, in March a senior partner said he did not
know whether the shelters were ever built.
