THE OFFICIALS
Exporters contact government (DTI) if licences required.
Tony Steadman was head of the export licensing unit when
many UK exports to Iraq were approved.  A grade seven
civil servant, he would advise the trade minister how
export guidelines should be interpreted.  He also
briefed Alan Clark before the crucial meeting with
machine tool company executives in January 1988 on how
they should fill in their export applications.
THE COMMITTEE
If licences were required, applications would go to the
inter-departmental committee. This consisted of officials
from the DTI, the Ministry of Defence and the Foreign
Office.  In 1988 the committee met 12 times, in 1989
nine times and in 1990 11 times.  The IDC was set up
in early 1980s to deal specifically with licences
for Iran and Iraq.  In 1989 the value of export licence
applications approved totalled Pounds 50m for Iran and
Pounds 130m for Iraq.  Those refused amounted to Pounds
70m for Iran and Pounds 20m for Iraq.  In the period
up to the following June - just before Iraq's invasion
of Kuwait - approvals were Pounds 120m for Iran and
Pounds 75m for Iraq.  Those refused were Pounds 5m for
Iran and Pounds 1m for Iraq.
THE MINISTERS
In difficult cases, applications were referred to ministers
This would normally be at minister of state level -
William Waldegrave, Alan Clark and Lor Trefgame - for most
of the period involved.  But evidence given to the
supergun inquiry by a Foreign Office official confirmed
that it could be any minister from secretary of state down.
THE CLIENTS*
Hutteen State Establishment:  Subordinate to Iraq's State
Organisation of Technical Industries (SOTI) which is
responsible fo the conventional defence industries.  SOTI
is in turn responsible to both the Ministry of Defence
and the Ministry of Industry and Minerals.  Hutteen is
the main ammunition manufacturing plant in Iraq.
Naser Establishment for Mechanical Industries: A plant
involved in armaments manufacture.  Among other things
it sought to buy moulding machinery to produce
polyurethane internal filler parts for missiles.
* For machine tools, weapons and defence-related equipment
