<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 92 / GEC to restore pay-offs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNION negotiators yesterday claimed victory when GEC Avery, the
Birmingham-based weighing equipment subsidiary of the UK electronics and
electrical engineering group, agreed to restore an enhanced redundancy pay
agreement for more than 2,000 workers.
The agreement, due to be signed today, wins back the right to redundancy pay
for workers employed before April 6. It had been cut about two years ago as
part of an economy drive. The move follows a damages award by the High Court
to a former employee made redundant on inferior terms. The company has
agreed to pay unions' court costs of Pounds 130,000.
The company does not accept the unions' argument that redundancy pay had
formed part of workers' contracts. The new agreement sets redundancy pay on
a contractual footing for the first time.
'At the end of this process we have achieved an agreement with which we are
satisfied,' the company said. It refused to comment on the detail of the
agreement.
The company has agreed to pay 60 former employees who had been made
redundant on inferior pay compensation equivalent to the enhanced pay, as
well as 15 per cent interest.
The MSF technical and professional union said the company's concession added
weight to growing evidence that almost all GEC companies, employing 80,000
workers in the UK, would have to reassess their policy of squeezing
redundancy pay.
</TEXT>
